Yeah.  It's a command-line program, so all the parameters needed are given when you run it.  You'd use a command like "nesasm file.asm" to do it.  Also in windows, I think you have to create a shortcut to do it, but you can make it keep the window open after it's finished running.<br /><br />I think it's best to use a text editor that can call other programs.  I use ConTEXT myself.  <a href="http://www.context.cx/" class="postlink">http://www.context.cx/</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Mon Jun 13, 2005 7:00 pm</p><hr />
